1) View beginning of a file
head file.txt

Common variants
head -n 5 file.txt        # First 5 lines
head -n -5 file.txt       # All except last 5 lines
head -c 20 file.txt       # First 20 bytes
head -q file1 file2       # No headers when multiple files
head -v file1 file2       # Always show headers

2) tail — View end of a file
tail file.txt

Common variants
tail -n 10 file.txt       # Last 10 lines
tail -n +5 file.txt       # Start from line 5
tail -c 50 file.txt       # Last 50 bytes
tail -f file.txt          # Follow file in real time (logs)
tail -F file.txt          # Follow even if file is recreated


3) cat — Concatenate & display files
cat file.txt

Common variants

cat file1 file2           # Merge and display
cat file1 file2 > out.txt # Merge into new file
cat -n file.txt           # Show line numbers
cat -b file.txt           # Number non-empty lines
cat -s file.txt           # Remove repeated blank lines
cat -E file.txt           # Show end-of-line ($)
cat -T file.txt           # Show tabs as ^I

Create file
cat > file.txt
# type content, press Ctrl+D to save

