7) . Main Wildcards
* → Matches any number of characters
ls *.txt
✔ Matches: a.txt, file.txt, notes.txt

Wildcards in Linux are special characters used by the **shell** to match filenames or patterns—similar to SQL `LIKE`, but used mostly with commands like `ls`, `cp`, `rm`, etc.

---

# 🌟 1. Main Wildcards

## `*` → Matches any number of characters

```bash id="8tvfdx"
ls *.txt
```

✔ Matches: `a.txt`, `file.txt`, `notes.txt`

```bash id="5jwh88"
ls file*
```

✔ Matches: `file1`, `fileA.txt`, `file_backup.log`

---

## `?` → Matches exactly one character

```bash id="e9s1hn"
ls file?.txt
```

✔ Matches: `file1.txt`, `fileA.txt`
❌ Not: `file10.txt`

---

## `[]` → Matches a range or set of characters

```bash id="knwy86"
ls file[123].txt
```

✔ Matches: `file1.txt`, `file2.txt`, `file3.txt`

```bash id="3ggs7y"
ls file[a-c].txt
```

✔ Matches: `filea.txt`, `fileb.txt`, `filec.txt`

---

## `[! ]` → Negation (NOT in set)

```bash id="q70syc"
ls file[!1].txt
```

✔ Matches: all except `file1.txt`

---

